According to the textbook Gaussian Process in Machine Learning, it is given that \begin{align*}
p(w\mid X,y) &\propto \exp\left(-\frac{1}{2\sigma_n^2}(y-X^Tw)(y-X^Tw)\right)\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}w^T\Sigma_{p}^{-1}w\right) \\
&\propto \exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}(w-\bar{w})^T\left(\frac{1}{\sigma_n^2}XX^T + \Sigma_p^{-1}\right)(w-\bar{w})\right)
\end{align*}
 where $\bar{w} = \sigma_n^{-2}(\sigma_n^{-2}XX^T + \Sigma_p^{-1})^{-1}Xy$. I can't really understand how the first step leads to the second step. Can someone kindly show me how the derivation is done? Thanks

$$\begin{align*}
\int \frac{du}{\sqrt{a^2-u^2}} &= \sin^{-1}\left(\frac{u}{a}\right) + K\\
\int \frac{du}{a^2+u^2} &= \frac{1}{a}\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{u}{a}\right) + K \end{align*}$$ Always wondered why but I had no idea.
